Investigation into last Saturday’s explosion at Ilu-abo, Akure North local government area of Ondo State has been initiated by the inspector-general of Police, Muhammed Adamu. The IGP yesterday set up a fact-finding committee to unravel the cause of the blast, which destroyed several houses and other property in the area. The deputy inspector-general of police (Operation), Abdulmajid Ali, who briefed the Ondo State governor, Oluwarotimi Akeredolu, on what the police had done so far, said that members of the committee included officers from the Police Bomb Disposal Squad (Explosive Ordinance Disposal Unit. Ali, who visited the governor after he inspecting the site of the explosion, said that the officials of the geological survey agency had taken sample of the soil and promised that the committee would come out with an acceptable report. The DIG, who was accompanied on the visit by the director-general of Geological Survey Agency of Nigeria, Dr. Kaka Imam, commended the state governor for his display of maturity when he visited the scene. He said that the police were working to unravel the mystery behind the blast. Akeredolu, who commended the police for the steps they had taken, lauded the state commissioner of police, Undie Adie, for being on his toes since the tragic incident occurred. He noted that while he was not against other views, particularly that of a university don, who claimed that the incident was caused by an asteriod, he is still relying on the initial information he got from the police commissioner. “I am not saying the professor was right or wrong and I am not making any conclusion. I have been speaking with some experts and they said if we were unable to found debris of the shattered truck within one kilometre radius from the spot of the incident, that shows the incident was not caused by explosive devices,” he said.